.TH "CONFIG.TOML" "5" "" "Project Kennel" "File Formats"
.SH NAME
config.toml \- Project Kennel user CLI configuration
.SH SYNOPSIS
~/.config/kennel/config.toml, /etc/kennel/config.toml, /usr/lib/kennel/config.toml
.SH DESCRIPTION
config.toml holds conveniences for the \fBkennel\fR(1) CLI: where it searches for templates, signing keys, and run policies while authoring. It is safe to edit as a user \(em it only steers the CLI's search, never enforcement. The daemon enforces against its own locked trust store (system.toml's trust_dir) regardless of anything here.
.PP
Search order, highest priority first: ~/.config/kennel/config.toml (or $XDG_CONFIG_HOME), /etc/kennel/config.toml, then the vendor copy. A set list \fBreplaces\fR the built\-in three\-layer default for that key.
.SH FIELDS
Each is a list of absolute paths (no ~ expansion).
.TP
\fBtemplate_dirs\fR \(em array of paths
Where compile/validate resolve <name>@<version>.
.TP
\fBkey_dirs\fR \(em array of paths
The authoring trust store. Note the trust split: templates verify only against the SYSTEM stores, never ~/.config/kennel/keys.
.TP
\fBpolicy_dirs\fR \(em array of paths
Where kennel run <name> resolves a policy by name.
.SH FILES
.TP
\fI~/.config/kennel/keys/\fR
User signing keys (valid for run policies, not templates).
.SH SEE ALSO
\fBkennel\fR(1), \fBkennel\-policy\fR(1), \fBsystem.toml\fR(5)
